                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Dygar wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">If the philosophy is that these aa's are only intended for players who've maxed all other aa's due to their price/value ratio then they should have just made a pre-requisite for them rather than just charging so much that they'd be unattractive to anyone with a choice.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Why?  What's wrong with pricing them high instead?  Either means winds up with the same result, stuff like SCM gets chosen way before Secondary Forte.  The only difference is the rate at which you tuck forte under your belt (once you've decided to get it), but at that point, what else are you going to spend AA on?
<br />

<br />
As far as a question of value compared to AA cost:  An alternate ability *always* has the correct value/cost.  You'll buy <insert AA here> when it's cost/value makes sense to you.  The only catch is value changes over time and as you earn other AA.  If they introduced an AA that simply did a social where you bend that mez-breaking asshat over your knee and spank the hell out of them, and had it cost 100 AA... eventually people would buy it, if only because they ran outta everything else first.  Cost/value would balance.
<br />

<br />
From what I've seen, in general, PoP AA usually falls behind original AA (specifically Archetype stuffs) as far as bang for buck.  Costs more, less impact, why would this suddenly be an issue for GoD AA?
<br />

<br />
Not sure if that made sense.  Pad Thai briefly took over my brain and made me post.</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br /><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=712271" target="_blank" class="postlink">Kurim</a> -- Marshall Overlord
